  "content": "<h1 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸŒ¿ Genome Skim: Organelle Genome Assembly</h1><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>High-Quality Organelle Genomes from Low-Coverage Sequencing</strong></p><p class=\"text-node\">Genome skimming is a cost-effective sequencing approach that targets high-copy genomic regions - chloroplast (plastid) and mitochondrial genomes - using shallow whole-genome sequencing. By leveraging the naturally high copy number of organellar DNA (5-10% chloroplast, 1-2% mitochondrial), this method efficiently recovers complete organelle genomes without the expense of deep nuclear genome sequencing.</p><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nf-core/genomeskim/master/docs/images/nf-core-genomeskim_logo_light.png\" alt=\"nf-core/genomeskim workflow\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\"><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ”¬ What is Genome Skimming?</h2><p class=\"text-node\">Genome skimming (also called shallow whole-genome sequencing) sequences the entire genome at low nuclear coverage (~0.05-2X) but achieves deep coverage of high-copy regions:</p><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸŒ± Chloroplast DNA (plastome):</strong> 120-200 kb circular genome, typically 30-100X coverage from skimming</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>âš¡ Mitochondrial DNA (mitogenome):</strong> Variable size (200-2500 kb), typically 10-50X coverage from skimming</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ§¬ Nuclear ribosomal DNA (nrDNA):</strong> 18S, 5.8S, 26S genes and ITS spacers</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ” Repetitive elements:</strong> Transposons and tandem repeats</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ¯ Key Features</h2><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Quality Control & Filtering</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“Š FastQC/MultiQC:</strong> Comprehensive quality assessment of raw sequencing reads</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>âœ‚ï¸ Adapter trimming:</strong> Remove technical sequences and low-quality bases</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ” Read filtering:</strong> Quality score filtering and length thresholds</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Organelle Genome Assembly</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸŒ¿ Chloroplast assembly:</strong> De novo assembly using GetOrganelle or NOVOPlasty seed-and-extend algorithms</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>âš¡ Mitochondrial assembly:</strong> Assembly of plant, animal, or fungal mitochondrial genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ”„ Circular genome reconstruction:</strong> Automatic detection and resolution of circular organelle genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“ Annotation:</strong> Automated gene prediction and functional annotation</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Assembly Validation</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>âœ… Coverage analysis:</strong> Per-base coverage depth across assembled genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ¯ Completeness checking:</strong> Verification of conserved organellar genes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“Š Assembly statistics:</strong> N50, total length, GC content, circularity</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ’¡ Why Use Genome Skimming?</h2><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Cost-Effective</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ’° Low sequencing cost:</strong> 1-5 million reads per sample sufficient (vs. 100M+ for nuclear genomes)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ”¬ High multiplexing:</strong> Sequence 96+ samples per Illumina lane</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>âš¡ Fast turnaround:</strong> Library prep to results in days, not weeks</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Versatile Applications</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸŒ³ Plant phylogenomics:</strong> Resolve evolutionary relationships using chloroplast genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ›ï¸ Museum specimens:</strong> Extract genomes from herbarium material up to 80+ years old</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ”¬ Biodiversity surveys:</strong> Rapid species identification and barcoding</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ§¬ Population genetics:</strong> Organellar DNA variation studies</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“š Reference genomes:</strong> Generate organelle references for non-model organisms</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Robust to Degraded DNA</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸº Ancient DNA:</strong> Works with degraded, low-quantity DNA (as low as 500 pg)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ‚ Herbarium specimens:</strong> Successful with dried, pressed plant material</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ§ª Ethanol-preserved samples:</strong> Ideal for museum and field collections</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ“‹ Input Requirements</h2><p class=\"text-node\">Your input is a CSV or TSV samplesheet specifying FASTQ files:</p><pre class=\"block-node\"><code>sample,fastq_1,fastq_2\nplant_species_1,sample1_R1.fastq.gz,sample1_R2.fastq.gz\nplant_species_2,sample2_R1.fastq.gz,sample2_R2.fastq.gz\nherbarium_specimen,specimen_R1.fastq.gz,specimen_R2.fastq.gz</code></pre><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Recommended Sequencing Parameters</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Platform:</strong> Illumina (HiSeq, NovaSeq, MiSeq)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Read length:</strong> 100-150 bp paired-end</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Coverage:</strong> 1-5 million read pairs per sample (0.05-0.5X nuclear coverage)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Insert size:</strong> 300-500 bp</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ“Š Output Results</h2><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Assembled Genomes</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ§¬ FASTA sequences:</strong> Complete chloroplast and mitochondrial genome assemblies</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“ GenBank files:</strong> Annotated genomes with gene features</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ—ºï¸ GFF3 annotations:</strong> Gene positions and functional annotations</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ”„ Circular plots:</strong> Visualization of circular genome structures</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Quality Metrics</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“ˆ Coverage profiles:</strong> Per-base sequencing depth across genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“Š Assembly statistics:</strong> Length, N50, GC%, gene completeness</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>âœ… Validation reports:</strong> Conserved gene presence/absence</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“‹ MultiQC report:</strong> Comprehensive quality control summary</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Supporting Files</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“ Read alignments:</strong> BAM files mapping reads to assembled genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“Š Assembly graphs:</strong> De Bruijn graph visualization</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>ğŸ“ Log files:</strong> Detailed assembly and annotation logs</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ“ Common Use Cases</h2><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Plant Systematics & Phylogenomics</h3><p class=\"text-node\">Chloroplast genomes (~150 kb, 80-130 genes) are ideal phylogenetic markers:</p><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\">Highly conserved gene order and content</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Sufficient variation for species-level resolution</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Uniparentally inherited (maternal in most plants)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">No recombination - clean phylogenetic signal</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Conservation Genomics</h3><p class=\"text-node\">Extract organellar genomes from:</p><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\">Endangered species with limited sample availability</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Historical herbarium specimens for temporal comparisons</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Environmental DNA (eDNA) samples</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Non-invasively collected samples (seeds, leaves)</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">Crop & Plant Breeding</h3><p class=\"text-node\">Organelle genome applications in agriculture:</p><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\">Cytoplasmic male sterility (CMS) studies</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Organellar trait inheritance patterns</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Domestication and breeding history</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\">Hybrid identification and verification</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ”§ Assembly Algorithms</h2><h3 class=\"heading-node\">GetOrganelle</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Strategy:</strong> Iterative read recruitment and assembly</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Best for:</strong> Plants, algae, fungi - diverse organelle structures</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Advantages:</strong> No seed sequence required, handles complex structures</p></li></ul><h3 class=\"heading-node\">NOVOPlasty</h3><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Strategy:</strong> Seed-and-extend algorithm</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Best for:</strong> Standard chloroplast and mitochondrial genomes</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Advantages:</strong> Fast, memory-efficient, works with distant seed sequences</p></li></ul><h2 class=\"heading-node\">ğŸ“š Expected Assembly Sizes</h2><ul class=\"list-node\"><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Plant chloroplasts:</strong> 115-165 kb (typical angiosperm)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Plant mitochondria:</strong> 200-2,500 kb (highly variable)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Animal mitochondria:</strong> 15-20 kb (compact, no introns)</p></li><li><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Fungal mitochondria:</strong> 20-200 kb</p></li></ul><p class=\"text-node\"><strong>Perfect for Research in:</strong> Plant systematics â€¢ Phylogenomics â€¢ Conservation biology â€¢ Biodiversity surveys â€¢ Herbarium genomics â€¢ Crop evolution â€¢ DNA barcoding â€¢ Population genetics â€¢ Ancient DNA studies</p><p class=\"text-node\">Built with <a class=\"link\" href=\"https://www.nextflow.io/\" target=\"_blank\">Nextflow</a> â€¢ Powered by <a class=\"link\" href=\"https://nf-co.re/genomeskim/\" target=\"_blank\">nf-core/genomeskim</a> â€¢ Containerized execution â€¢ Reproducible workflows</p>",
